  "text": "Large NMJ boutons (Ͼ3 m, typically 3-5 m) in normal Drosophila third instar larvae show characteristic patterns of SV pools [CITATION_1] . Wild-type boutons loaded with high K ϩ always incorporate FM1-43 dye in a circular pattern with the fluorescence restricted to cortical regions underlying the plasma membrane and an absence of signal in the central regions of the bouton (Fig. 3A) . This dye incorporation shows that the recycling SV pool filled via high-K ϩ stimulation is spatially restricted in a characteristic peripheral ring. In contrast, the bouton interior contains a reserve pool of SVs that are accessed only under conditions of intense transmission demand (Kuromi and Kidokoro, 1998). Previous studies have shown that the reserve pool can only be loaded with FM1-43 after high-frequency (Ͼ30 Hz) stimulation or after complete elimination and mass renewal of the SV population with the Dynamin mutant shibire TS1 Kidokoro, 1998, 2000) . We wanted to determine whether the ready/reserve SV pool boundary is maintained in stoned mutants and whether Stoned proteins may play a role in the spatial dynamics of SV recycling.",
